void Netlist::clusterSize ( std::vector< unsigned int > &  netWeights) const

Create net weights by mean of the cluster size. Return the result to the array netWeights

Create net weights by mean of the cluster size. Return the result to the array netWeights. Net's weight is 0 if it is marked as fixed. (A net is marked as fixed if it is an interface net or it connects to a fixed cell.)

unsigned int Netlist::firstChoice ( const std::vector< unsigned int > &  netWeights)

Find a set of candidate nets by FC algorithm. The nets selected are marked as visited.

Returns:
the number of nets selected. The algorithm starts with sorting nets in non-increasing order according to the net weights. Assume that net weights are bounded by a small value so that bucket sorting algorithm is used. In [khmetis], the aurthers commented that the rate of contractions by this method may be too fast. They imposed a constraint that the contraction process will stop if certain ratio is reach (1.7 in their case). In MLPart, similar constraint is set (1.3 in their case).

Note: This scheme creates less randomness than minimumNetCover.

void Netlist::initWeightList ( GDList< Vertex > &  L)

Sort the cells in decending order according to their weight and return the result to L.

Sort the vertices by weight in descending order. Return result to the list L. If the kinds of weights are small (because the cells are from only a few master copies), then the function runs in nearly linear time. The worst case is O(N logN) time.

bool Netlist::isVILEOk ( double  balTol,
int  numParts 
)
Returns:
true if this netlist can eventually guarantee provide legal partition by FM iteration

Check if FM iteration can guarantee eventually produce legal solution with any (include illegal) initial partitions. The bound can be calculated by using a simple pigeonhole arugument. That is, if we want to gurantee a sequence of single moves can eventually produce legal result, at least sum of certain "small" vertices/cells has to be larger than the total weight divided by the number of partitions. This checking runs in O(N logN) where N is the number of vertices. (Assume no fixed cells)

unsigned int Netlist::maximalMatchingNets ( const std::vector< unsigned int > &  netWeights)

Find a maximal matching of nets (edges) , i.e., a subset such that no two nets in shares a common cell (endpoint) and every net in shares at least a common cell with some net in .A cell that does not connect to any nets in is called isolated cell. A net weight is the sum of cell weight here. The objective is to minimize the total net weights.

First, we explore a similar Primal-Dual algorithm described in [1] that solves the graph weighted vertex cover problem. We generalize the idea of the algorithm for hypergraph. Instead of vertex cover, here we find the hyperedge cover , i.e., a subset such that, for each cell, at least one of connected nets belongs to . Then based on the solution of hyperedge cover, we perform the post processing such that no two nets in share a common cell by removing nets or moving nets. The process can be performed locally.

The overall run time is linear, assuming that the maximum degree is bounded by a small value.

Parameters:
netWeightsnet weights
Returns:
number of nets selected

Reference [1]: Program 2.7 in "Complexity and Approximation: Combinatorial Optimization Problems and their Approximability Properties.

unsigned int Netlist::maximumIndependentSet ( const std::vector< unsigned int > &  netWeight)

Maximize Independent Set (Nets) by greedy algorithm. Take O(N logN) time.

Find an independent set by Greedy algorithm. The nets selected are marked as visited.

Returns:
the number of nets selected. The algorithm starts with sorting nets in non-increasing order first according to the net weights. Assume that net weights are bounded by a small value so that bucket sorting algorithm is used.

unsigned int Netlist::minimumNetCover ( const std::vector< unsigned int > &  netWeights)

Find a minimum net (edge) cover , i.e., a subset such that for each cell, at least one of connected nets belongs to . A net weight is the sum of cell weight here. The objective is to minimize the total net weights. We explore a similar Primal-Dual algorithm described in [1] that solves the graph weighted vertex cover problem. We generalize the idea of the algorithm for hypergraph. Instead of vertex cover, here we find the hyperedge cover. The overall run time is linear, assuming that the maximum degree is bounded by a small value. The solution by the Primal-Dual algorithm is guaranteed bounded by times the optimal solution where is the maximum degree of nets.

Parameters:
netWeightsnet weights
Returns:
number of nets selected

Reference [1]: Program 2.7 in "Complexity and Approximation: Combinatorial Optimization Problems and their Approximability Properties.

Find a minimum net (edge) cover E'', i.e., a subset E'' E such that for each cell, at least one of connected nets belongs to E''. A net weight is the sum of cell weight here. The objective is to minimize the total net weights. We explore a similar Primal-Dual algorithm described in [1] that solves the graph weighted vertex cover problem. We generalize the idea of the algorithm for hypergraph. Instead of vertex cover, here we find the hyperedge cover. The overall run time is linear, assuming that the maximum degree is bounded by a small value. The solution by the Primal-Dual algorithm is guaranteed bounded by K times the optimal solution where K is the maximum degree of nets.
